<DATE>940919
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
White Heat on BBC2 is one of the most thoughtful series for a long time.
Today's episode considers standardisation and its effects, showing how it
has been central to the development of technology in the past century.
Babbage was unable to realise his design for a mechanical calculator in
1830, arguably a prototype computer, partly because of disagreements with
his engineer but also because of the lack of standardised components. Now
that so much has been standardised, and with genetic engineering a reality,
the programme asks: 'Will the temptation to standardise human beings be
resisted?' (8.00). Happily, GF Newman's dramas always stir things up. He is
a radical who sees it as his job to question the accepted and flout
authority. He reckons medical science has become 'wholly decadent and
self-serving' and his two-part drama The Healer, about a newly-appointed
senior house officer, reflects this (9.30 BBC1). Part 2 tomorrow. The
X-Files is the latest in that stream of American weirdo-drama which began
with 'Twin Peaks'. This time the theme is investigation of the paranormal
(9.30 BBC2).
</TEXT>
