<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Sport: Talk turns to football
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Quite often I spend Sunday at my parents' home, where the languid hours are
given structure by the Sky Television broadcast of a Premier League football
match. 'What's the game today? Ah, that'll be a good one,' my father will
say to me during lunch. In so doing he speaks the words which begin the
afternoon ritual.
By 2.45pm the television will be tuned to Sky Sports, the better to savour
the moments before the programme begins: within the flickering images we
conjure those of the perfect football match. During the hours of build-up to
the game itself, which Sky fills with prognostications and statistics, we
create in the living room a studio debate of our own. Back and forth go the
comments: 'Who's going to win it?' - 'Newcastle, 3-0' - 'No, Spurs will get
one' - 'Their bubble's burst' - 'Think they'll go down?' - 'Think Newcastle
will win the league?' - 'Their bubble might burst'.
At 4pm, the moment of kick-off, we will have reached a peak of expectation.
For the first 10 minutes we will follow play like metal detectors moving
along the ground. Then it will become apparent that the game is no longer
exerting the hold over us that it should. By approximately 4.20pm, my eyes
will be irresistibly drawn to the Sunday papers, my mother will have removed
herself from her studio chair and my father will be fast asleep.
To us, clearly, the true joy of football lies in the paraphernalia that goes
with it, and especially in those meaningless, circuitous, wonderfully
comforting conversations that anyone with the slightest idea about the game
can have. When I worked in the theatre, we would talk endlessly about other
actors and directors - 'Oh, he was in his hamlet' - 'Oh she auditioned for
that' - with a good deal more zeal than we would bring to the serious
business of acting and directing. In the world of sport, the subject of the
conversations may be very different but the conversations themselves are
exactly the same.
Of course, many of the people who indulge in football chit-chat are true
lovers of the game, capable of staying awake throughout an entire Sunday
afternoon with Sky Television. Sometimes I have one of these conversations
with my mother's window cleaner, a diehard Luton Town supporter. It is
obvious that we are saying the same things for different reasons. I am doing
it for the pleasure of affirming my knowledge, and he's doing it for the
pleasure of talking about the thing that he loves.
To me, the thought of going to watch Luton Town is entirely unappealing, as
indeed is the thought of going to most football matches. And I suspect that
is true of a large number of people who purport to love football. What they
love is knowing about it. They love being au fait with transfer deals and
intrigues: they love talking about it. These are the people who were tapped
into by Nick Hornby's Fever Pitch. That book was written by a true fan of
football, but its genius is that it spoke not merely to those who loved the
game, but to those who loved the paraphernalia of the game.
And the great thing is that it is so easy to talk about football. What do I
know about Luton Town? Nothing. But by deploying a few totemic phrases, for
example referring to the fact that the manager - Pleaty - has no money with
which to build his teams, I can hold a conversation with someone who has
seen them play practically every weekend of his adult life. Ridiculous, yet
true.
Sometimes I wonder, though, who really does know anything about football.
Who really understands its infinite but oddly banal complexities? Managers
are the avowed experts, but look at the howlers that most of them make.
Look, too, at Terry Venables, hailed as the man who would revitalise
England, reduced to recalling most of the players used by the reviled Graham
Taylor; where is the magical knowledge that can unearth the unexpected? For
heaven's sake, even I could have picked the team that played recently
against the USA.
Football is, in fact, the most slippery and mysterious of sports. So much
should be possible, but so often this potential turns to predictability.
There must be thousands of ways in which a team can score, but goals almost
always occur simply through luck. The lacklustre World Cup final between
Brazil and Italy proved that football can never be relied upon to entertain;
last week's UEFA cup defeat of Blackburn by part-timers Trelleborgs proved
that mediocrity can always triumph over talent. Really, sometimes one
wonders why anyone likes football at all. At the moment, sated after days of
unrelenting bombardment, I have as much appetite for it as I would have for
the last meal of a gourmet weekend.
But you still can't stop me talking it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7941 Sports Clubs, Managers, and Promoters.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
