<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plays by G F Newman usually create quite a stir - Law and Order, for
example, led to allegations of bias and a ban on the BBC filming in jails
for a year - so there is some anticipation about his latest, The Healer
(Tonight, 9.30-10.45pm, BBC1). Paul Rhys plays the new boy on the hospital
ward who discovers he has miraculous powers, with a laying on of hands
proving far more effective than anything he can prescribe. He faces
hostility from within the medical establishment and accusations of quackery
from the press. Geraldine James plays his only white-coated ally. Although
the script is unevenly paced, Newman's polemical thrust drives the drama
along. This after all is the man who banned meat from the catering vans
during filming. The concluding part will be shown tomorrow (9.30-10.25pm).
An astonishing 60 per cent of the world's money is now held in off-shore
accounts according to the Panorama team whose three-parter on the subject,
Dirty Money (Tuesday, September 20, 10.25-11.05pm, BBC1) ends with a look at
Grand Cayman. This Caribbean island is said to be the fifth largest
financial centre in the world, with over Dollars 600bn passing through its
500 banks every year. Gavin Hewitt talks to Jack Blum, a US investigator
into the BCCI affair, who argues that offshore centres provide a safe haven
for money launderers by putting a stop to any serious scrutiny. We also get
to hear from a man who claims to have laundered hundreds of millions of
dollars through British dependent territories in the West Indies. 'I
regarded it as easier than brushing your teeth,' he boasts.
After a seven-year sabbatical, University Challenge returns to television
(Wednesday, September 21, 8.30-9.00pm, BBC2) but on a new channel and with a
new presenter. Jeremy Paxman, having honed his interrogating skills on
politicians, will be showing his nicer nature by throwing questions at
undergraduates, beginning with the University of Birmingham and Aberdeen
University. The revival is due as much to nostalgia as it is to the
intrinsic worth of the programme. So expect to hear the phrase 'your starter
for ten'. Whether Paxman, however, will feel comfortable about saying 'well
remembered, Queens', as Bamber Gascoigne was wont to, is a moot point.
The spoof chat show, Knowing Me, Knowing You With Alan Partridge (Friday,
10.00-10.30pm, BBC2) gathers strength with its second episode. This spin-off
from the Radio Four series is coarser in its approach than its progenitor
but there are some exquisite moments. Tonight our man in the bad wig
interviews Daniella Forest, the new agony aunt for a girlie magazine, who is
described as 'a quality guest from top to bottom and back again' and a
thespian couple - Tany Beaumont and Gary Barker, the bad boy of Beverly
Hills. The team behind this - Steve Coogan, Patrick Marber, Rebecca Front
and Doon Mackichan - represents the latest wave of ex-Oxbridge comics,
following on from John Cleese et al in the 1960s, the Not The Nine O'Clock
News team in the late 1970s and Stephen Fry and his coterie in the 1980s.
</TEXT>
