<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / This Week: Film/Video
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Should comedy comfort or disturb? If you have never entered the world of
Czech animator Jan Svankmajer before, you should try his Faust, opening in
London this week. The most inventive model-worker and puppeteer in modern
cinema, his last feature was a black-comedy version of Lewis Carroll's
Alice.
Faust takes marionette mayhem even further: bizarrely stylised faces and
figures; bits of nightmare surrealism; pastiche touches of 'antiquity' -
Svankmajer approaches Christopher Marlowe as if by a route through Spitting
Image and Hieronymus Bosch.
If you prefer your humour without a hint of the hellish, there is the new
City Slickers 2. Raved over across the Atlantic, this second cowboy comedy
has Billy Crystal again as star-screenwriter, plus a Jack Palance still
going strong after those Oscar show press-ups when he won Best Supporting
Actor for Slickers 1.
Peter Greenaway's The Falls is the video treat of the week and ideal for
those who like their comedy neither black nor wacky, but very dry. Three
hours of spoof research into a group of 'mysterious' accident victims, the
1980 film was made before Greenaway slipped into mainstream movie-making
with The Draughtsman's Contract. But it has all his gnomic wit, his love of
the absurd and his eye for jewelled, eccentric imagery.
Nobody does comedy better than Woody Allen: even when there is little to
smile at in his own life. With his new film, Bullets Over Broadway headed
for late-year British release after delighting audiences (including me) at
the recent Venice film festival, why not limber up by re-seeing the
20-year-old Annie Hall and the one-year-old Manhattan Murder Mystery? Both
are at the National Film Theatre this week.
With MMM also out on video, you can make up your mind whether Allen's humour
has really hit the skids - as American commentators inferred from the film's
poor performance at the US box office - or whether scandal has simply
clouded everyone's minds. In my view, he is still the funniest man in the
world, and his newest comedies among his best.
</TEXT>
<XX>
