<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Delegates are advised to reject minimum wage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, yesterday called on his party
to reject proposals for the introduction of a rigid minimum wage, urging
them to back 'flexible' policies on the economy and the labour market.
As Liberal Democrats prepared to debate the economic policies with which
they will fight the next election, Mr Ashdown told delegates that they must
issue a clear rejection of wage controls at this week's conference if they
are to underline the distinction between their party's economic policies and
those of Labour.
In an eve-of-conference speech the Liberal Democrat leader poured scorn on
Labour's 'umbilical attachment' to a rigid national minimum wage, which, he
said, was foisted on them by the public-sector unions. Instead, he urged the
introduction of 'wage watchdogs' which would 'investigate' allegations of
exploitation by employers.
He said: 'The right way to tackle exploitation is through targeted policies
 -decentralised, flexible, running with the grain of the market - policies
that protect both the wages and the jobs of the lowest paid.'
Senior party officials admit, however, that the conference may endorse a
call for more rigid wage regulation tomorrow in its discussion of
employment. This would include the setting of a regional minimum hourly rate
of pay by a Low Pay Commission.
With debate already raging over how the Liberal Democrats should deal with a
Labour party led by Mr Tony Blair, some of Mr Ashdown's colleagues believe
the party must clearly reject 'old-style' socialist policies.
They believe that the party will avoid calling for renationalisation in a
debate today in spite of discontent in the Liberal Democrats' heartland in
the west country.
The Liberal Democrat leader is also determined to avoid a clash with
delegates this week on the party's commitment to tax incomes over Pounds
100,000 a year at the rate of 60 per cent.
Mr Ashdown is understood to believe a recent Liberal Democrat resolution
calling for this level of taxation is far too punitive. The leader of the
party's Parliamentary Candidates' Association said at the weekend that the
party had 'pressed the self-destruct button' with its taxation policy.
Nevertheless, some senior party figures take comfort that this level of
taxation is less severe than the rate imposed by the Conservative government
for most of the 1980s.
</TEXT>
<XX>
