<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Action urged on electoral reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Charles Kennedy, the outgoing party president, called for determined
efforts to establish cross-party agreement on constitutional reform before
the next general election.
He warned that the legislative measures needed to introduce electoral reform
and other changes were almost certain to face formidable parliamentary
obstacles whatever the political complexion of the next government.
Mr Kennedy said: 'The way must be prepared well in advance, within parties
and across them, if constitutional measures are to be addressed.'
The crisis faced by Mr John Major over the Maastricht treaty on European
Union, when a government with an apparent working majority had been reduced
to a 'broken-back' state, underlined the hazards of constitutional bills.
Mr Kennedy suggested that, if the Conservatives lost power, their MPs in the
next parliament would be under pressure to close ranks and oppose any
constitutional reform.
He urged 'reformers of all political allegiances' to start discussions on
the desirability of constitutional change and on how to deliver it.
</TEXT>
