<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Council offers to open books
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour-controlled Birmingham city council yesterday invited the District
Auditor to examine its spending procedures in an attempt to clear the air
after newspaper allegations that councillors tried to buy votes in May's
local elections.
Announcing the decision to invite inspection of decisions taken under the
Pounds 7m Meeting Needs Across the City programme, Ms Theresa Stewart,
council leader, said she was confident that the district auditor would find
'no basis for these allegations and nothing improper'.
According to the allegations, published in the Sunday Times, money
supposedly earmarked for improving environmental conditions in deprived
areas was used instead to win over middle-class voters in vulnerable Labour
wards.
In the local elections Labour held its majority against the expectations of
many. One of its two gains was in middle-class Edgbaston, which had never
gone Labour before.
