<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Retailers of fitness products face legal fight with
franchiser
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Former retail franchisees of Weider Health &amp; Fitness, a subsidiary of the US
fitness and bodybuilding products group, are engaged in a legal battle with
the company.
Six former franchisees, running nine stores in England and Scotland,
terminated their contracts with Weider last year and changed the names of
their shops to Work-Out World. They said Weider had broken a verbal
agreement not to supply goods to other retailers, leaving them unable to
compete.
Weider withdrew an application for a High Court injunction last month to
stop the franchisees from trading, on the grounds of breach of contract. But
the company is now suing the franchisees for 'conspiracy to take away
Weider's business'.
The franchisees have been told the legal action is likely to continue even
though Weider's UK retail business was recently sold to a group run by
former Weider employees.
Three franchisees travelled to the US 10 days ago, where they secured a
promise from Mr Ben Weider, president of the International Federation of
Bodybuilders and younger brother of the group's founder, former bodybuilder
Mr Joe Weider, to investigate the case.
Weider UK refused to comment.
The franchisees say that when they entered their agreements in the late
1980s they had a verbal, though not written, commitment from Weider that it
would not supply its products to any other retailer, except for a limited
range at Argos, the catalogue retailer.
About 2 1/2 years ago, however, they found an increasing number of other
retail outlets being supplied with Weider goods.
As franchisees had to pay Weider 10 per cent royalties on all goods -
including non-Weider goods - sold, they say they could not compete with
other retailers on price. Five franchisees claim to have gone bankrupt as a
result.
One franchisee, who asked not to be named, said: 'When I went into this
business I was a layman. My understanding was that the term franchisee
implied something with trade exclusivity.'
The retailer said his weekly turnover fell from up to Pounds 7,000 a week to
between Pounds 3,000 and Pounds 3,500 after Weider goods began being stocked
by other retailers. He added that even before this, after paying Weider
Pounds 50,000 royalties out of his Pounds 500,000 annual turnover, he was
left with a profit of only Pounds 9,000.
The rebel franchisees say that while their contracts with Weider prevented
them from trading in the same area for two years after termination of the
contract, they had received legal advice suggesting this was not
enforceable.
They say they no longer sell Weider goods, and have changed their product
mix to include swimwear and athletic wear. They add that there is no
question of a 'conspiracy' to take business from Weider.
</TEXT>
