<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Guinness jealously guards liquid gold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More valuable than all the gold in the Bank of England? Casks of whisky lie
maturing in Guinness' warehouse complex in central Scotland. The whisky,
from more than 50 distilleries, will be stored for up to 25 years. Some 2
per cent of it evaporates each year, a loss known as 'the angels' share'.
Said to be the largest warehouse complex in Europe, the 250-acre site has 49
buildings each the size of a football pitch. Guinness, which reports its
interim results on Thursday, tries to keep the precise location secret,
although local people could hardly miss it.
Tradition has it that the stocks are worth more than the gold in the Bank of
England. The claim is impossible to verify but a back-of-the-envelope
calculation suggests the Bank can sleep easy in the knowledge that it, not
Guinness, sits on the biggest hoard of hard assets in the country.
Guinness' 1993 accounts show Pounds 1.47bn worth of maturing spirits stocks,
more than half of which are likely to be in the warehouse complex. But they
are carried at Guinness' manufacturing cost. The 'street value', including
hefty tax could be up to five times higher.
The Bank of England is no more forthcoming. The UK has 18.4m ounces of gold
reserves worth about Pounds 4.8bn. But it refuses to say how much of it lies
in its vaults beneath Threadneedle Street. Moreover, the vaults also contain
an unknown quantity of gold it stores for foreign clients.
The Bank welcomes speculation about Guinness' wealth.
An official said: 'For security reasons, we're glad of anything that takes
attention away from the gold in our vaults.'
</TEXT>
