<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Banks seek role in China unit trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British fund management companies will this week press the Chinese
government for permission to participate in introducing unit trusts to China
as a means of reducing the volatility of share prices on local stock
exchanges.
A mission to China by British Invisibles, the cross-sector organisation
which promotes invisible exports, is to seek access to the Chinese equity
market for fund and management companies, including the asset management
arms of UK banks and investment banks.
The 30-strong delegation, which will give seminars on aspects of regulatory
policy and financial practice in the City, will press for a more certain
framework of financial law to give overseas institutions certainty that
their contracts are binding.
The mission is the sixth by British Invisibles since 1980 and comes amid a
rapid growth in interest among financial institutions in gaining access to
China. Foreign banks have previously not been allowed to gather local
currency deposits or sell Chinese shares to local investors.
Mr Robin Box, vice-chairman of Kleinwort Benson, the investment bank, said
the Chinese government had accepted that the development of a unit trust
industry would help to curb stock-market volatility by channelling the flow
of retail investment.
Mr Fox said banks and investment banks with fund management arms would try
to persuade the government to allow them to take part in joint ventures with
local companies.
Lord Alexander, chairman of National Westminster Bank, said that the
uncertainty of Chinese law limited investment in the country. Banks were
made more reluctant to lend by the difficulty of obtaining legally binding
covenants on loans.
Mission leaders said they did not believe that UK companies were at a
disadvantage because of disagreements between the UK and Chinese governments
over Hong Kong. Mr Fox said that odd cases of discrimination had occurred
where 'a local official did not want to create a rumpus'.
Domestic share prices in China have fluctuated wildly this year. Events such
as the government's statement that it would allow foreigners to invest in
the 'A shares' that are currently restricted to local investors have sent
share prices up by more than 60 per cent.
</TEXT>
