<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Romford brewery heads for Beijing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Romford brewery, famous for its John Bull bitter, is to be shipped off to
China tank, tun and keg to help slake thirsts in one of the world's
fastest-growing beer markets.
San Miguel, the Philippines-based brewer, has bought the complete plant and
will re-erect it about 100 miles south of Beijing. It will use it to brew
its own lager, which is one of the best-selling foreign brands in China.
A victim of over-capacity in the UK market, the brewery was closed early
last year ending nearly 200 years of production on the site, which was the
original home of Ind Coope.
Mr Iain Oag of Carlsberg-Tetley, the seller, said: 'It was a sad but
necessary day.' The company pools the UK brewing interests of Carlsberg, the
Danish brewer, and Allied Domecq, the UK spirits group which today changes
its name from Allied-Lyons.
In addition to the Romford equipment, which can brew 1m barrels a year, San
Miguel is buying a bottling line from Carlsberg-Tetley's Northampton
brewery, which was closed a year ago. Carlsberg-Tetley declined to disclose
the sale price.
Much of the equipment dates from the early-1980s but some is newer. Most of
it is small enough to fit in containers but one 30-ft diameter tun, a
stainless steel separation vessel, will be cut in half and reassembled in
China.
China's annual beer consumption is running at only 8.4 litres a head
compared with 100 litres in the UK and 158 litres in Germany. But China is
already the third-largest producer in the world after the US and Germany.
UK consumption is falling by about 2 per cent a year. With production
running at about 34m barrels a year, the industry is operating at
over-capacity of between 15 per cent and 20 per cent.
</TEXT>
