<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Milk prices sour the cheesemakers: Companies face paying far
more in a liberalised market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cheesemakers are feeling the pinch from the impending deregulation of the
Pounds 3.3bn milk market in England and Wales, which is pushing up prices
for almost all buyers.
Mr Tony Craske, managing director of Abergavenny Fine Foods, which he claims
is the largest speciality cheesemaker in Wales, said he faces a 16 per cent
increase in the price of his supplies.
He said: 'We're competing at the supermarkets almost exclusively with
continental cheesemakers and I'm not sure we'll be able to pass on the rise
in price.'
Under liberalisation of the milk market on November 1 the Milk Marketing
Board, the government's statutory purchasing body, will be abolished. In its
place will be Milk Marque, a voluntary farmers' co-operative which has
already signed up 65 per cent of producers.
Since cheesemakers paid one of the lowest prices for supply under the milk
board's allocation system, they are facing the highest rises in the new free
market because they have to compete with all other milk buyers.
Mr Stephen Curtis, managing director of Horlicks, a mature-cheddar producer
in Ilminster, Somerset, said: 'I'm concerned and very angry with the
government for authorising a system which was almost certain to have this
effect.'
Mr Curtis is paying 18 per cent more for his supplies, which he believes
will be difficult to recover from a competitive marketplace.
Mr John Price, director-general of the Dairy Trade Federation, the dairy
industry group, said all manufacturing companies faced significant price
increases.
The federation has applied for a judicial review of the government's plans
for the milk industry. The hearing to decide whether to grant a judicial
review takes place tomorrow. If it is successful, the federation will push
for a decision to be speeded up so that a conclusion can be reached next
month, before the market is opened up.
Milk supplies in Britain are kept tight because of European Union quotas
which mean farmers can produce only 85 per cent of UK needs. Under the milk
board scheme prices were kept low by a rationing system which gave priority
to dairies selling liquid milk.
But the new free market means buyers can bid up supplies as they rush to
secure enough milk for their own uses. One producer in Lancashire has found
his demands were still scaled back by 60 per cent even though he was paying
3.2p per litre more for his milk under the new Milk Marque auction system.
Mr Paul Plowman, sales and marketing director at the milk board, said it was
too simplistic to compare the board's rationing system with the new auction
which offers specific service contracts.
He said: 'Today companies will be able to buy defined volumes and be able to
plan their businesses more effectively.' But many cheese producers disagree
with him, saying they will face more uncertainty in the new market.
Ironically, the price rises have led to uncertainty over the flotation of
Dairy Crest, the milk board's own processing arm, which was hoped to be sold
before the November launch. The flotation has been put off indefinitely.
One of the benefits of liberalising the market is to allow companies to buy
supplies directly from farmers. But small dairies and cheese producers
cannot afford to hire tankers or employ testing equipment to make collection
of the milk worthwhile.
Mr Craske said: 'For dairies using less than 3,000 gallons a day it's not a
proposition to buy directly from farmers.' Even larger dairy companies are
finding it difficult to secure supplies as Milk Marque has signed up 65 per
cent of milk production.
The price changes are forcing many small dairies and cheesemakers to
reconsider their business plans. Mr Craske has been trying to break into the
North American market with a promotion timed for St David's day next year,
but has been forced to reduce his efforts. 'We're squeezed so much on
margins - we don't have any money left for that sort of thing,' he said.
The Lancashire producer is planning to re-direct his business to the
production of cheeses such as Cheshire, Lancashire and Wensleydale in
smaller quantities, which is a more lucrative market niche than before. He
expects to give up exporting double Gloucester in 20kg blocks.
Many dairies believe imports will rush in to the UK market in November to
compete with higher-priced domestic products. Mild cheddar cheese is
expected to be the most competitive sector.
Mr Craske said: 'I can't believe it was one of the government's objectives
of milk privatisation to allow one company to hijack the nation's milk
supply and hold them to ransom at a hugely inflated price.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
