<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Financial team to advise Saudis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JEDDAH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Britain is to send a team of technical and financial experts to Saudi Arabia
to advise King Fahd on the Saudi government's fledgling privatisation
programme, Kevin Brown in Jeddah writes.
British officials said the king confirmed the Saudi government's growing
interest in privatisation during several hours of talks last night with Mr
John Major, the prime minister, who is on a week-long trip to Saudi Arabia,
Abu Dhabi and South Africa.
Officials said Britain had agreed to send two telecommunications experts to
advise on the possible sale of the state telephone company. Saudi Arabia has
given no formal indication of other industrial sectors which might be
privatised, but the petrochemical industry and the state-owned airlines are
thought to be prime candidates.
Saudi Arabia is believed to be considering the privatisation of parts of the
public sector to replenish reserves depleted by the cost of the Gulf war.
Declining real prices for oil exports and rising spending, particularly on
arms, have pushed the government's finances into deficit for 12 consecutive
years.
Mr Major also hopes to initiate privatisation discussions in South Africa,
where he arrives tomorrow for the first official visit by a British prime
minister since 1960.
Mr Anthony Nelson, the Treasury minister responsible for privatisation, will
have extensive talks with government and commercial officials to identify
state assets which could be sold.
