<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Confidence grows of 51% Royal Mail sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading supporters within the cabinet of privatisation of the Post Office
are confident that the government will press ahead with a majority sale of
the Royal Mail.
They believe, however, that formal approval for the sale of a 51 per cent
stake in the Royal Mail might signal an indefinite delay in the government's
equally controversial plan to open up the domestic gas market to
competition.
A final decision on the Post Office sale will be deferred until the
conclusion of the consultation period at the end of this month.
In spite of the opposition of a hard-core of Tory MPs, Mr Michael Heseltine,
trade and industry secretary, and Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, expect
the cabinet to adopt the preferred option set out in the government's white
paper in July.
Mr Clarke, in particular, believes that a decision in favour of
privatisation is essential to demonstrate that the government has maintained
its radical momentum.
Mr John Major is still wary about the potential political cost of a decision
which the Labour party says will signal a significant run-down in rural post
services and the closure of many village post offices. But Mr Douglas Hurd,
who in spite of his role as foreign secretary has emerged as a pivotal
figure in the cabinet debate over the future of the Post Office, is said by
aides to remain in favour of a 51 per cent sale.
On that basis, Downing Street officials expect Mr Major to give the go-ahead
for the sale. That would allow Mr Heseltine to announce the decision at the
Conservative party conference in mid-October. Ministers believe that strong
conference backing for the plan would put pressure on dissident backbench
MPs to fall into line.
The dissidents have been calling for a minority sale of the Royal Mail, with
the government retaining 51 per cent of the shares. But Mr Bill Cockburn,
the chief executive of the Post Office, has dismissed that idea as
'unworkable'.
On the assumption that a majority sale will go ahead, the Department of
Trade and Industry has already established a separate team to prepare the
legislation. The Treasury is also considering a number of financial
arrangements for a privatised Post Office.
The expectation that the sale will go ahead, however, has cast further
doubts over whether the government will meet its commitment to open up the
domestic gas market by April 1996. Ministers backing the break-up of the
monopoly enjoyed by British Gas acknowledge that it might be impossible to
fit legislation into the forthcoming parliamentary session alongside a Post
Office bill.
British Gas has also alarmed many Conservative MPs by insisting that
competition in the domestic market will lead to higher prices for millions
of consumers. The threatened price rises might be particularly steep in the
rural areas where Post Office privatisation is causing most public concern.
</TEXT>
