<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Societies watchdog softens on new code
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Building Societies Commission, the sector's statutory regulator, has
softened its guidance on how the Cadbury code of corporate governance should
apply to societies.
The new guidance, which was sent to society chief executives on Friday,
comes before government suggestions on ways in which society boards should
be more accountable to their millions of members.
These are expected to be published next week as a consultation paper which
makes up the second stage of the Treasury's review of building society
legislation.
The proposals will include reserving a small minority of board places for
non-executive directors elected by society members without a contest
involving candidates nominated by the board.
Provisional guidelines on corporate governance which were published last
year in the form of a draft prudential note were severely criticised by many
societies, which said they went beyond the Cadbury committee
recommendations.
Prudential notes have a particular status in the regulation of building
societies. Any society that does not comply with such a note normally has to
explain itself to the commission and might also find its credit rating
affected.
The final guidance still runs to almost 20 pages, but the commission now
says that only the three pages of the code of best practice will count in
terms of the requirement to offer an explanation to the regulator of any
failure to comply.
There are also some concessions in the substance - such as removal of the
requirement that boards include at least one member with relevant
professional expertise to direct a society's non-core activities.
</TEXT>
