<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / China seeks foreign funds for petrochemicals boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
China plans investment of Yn100bn (Pounds 7.5bn) in its outdated
petrochemical sector by the year 2000, with a big chunk of the funds coming
from abroad, including equity participation.
Mr Li Yizhong, vice president of the China Petrochemical Corporation,
promised an aggressive approach to capital raising on world markets to
overcome one of the acknowledged weak spots of the Chinese economy.
'It's apparent that we should resort to international capital markets other
than just rely on domestic funds to achieve our goals. . . utilising foreign
capital, especially direct investment, would be our long-term strategy,' Mr
Li told the Business Weekly newspaper.
He said that before 2000 China would give priority to revamping and
expanding existing facilities, especially those in coastal regions
accessible to crude oil imports.
Sino-foreign joint venture refineries would be allowed to sell part of their
product in the domestic market, Mr Li said.
China is negotiating investment deals with several big oil producers and
refiners, including Aramco, Saudi Arabia's state oil company, for the
establishment of joint venture refineries.
China's need for additional refining capacity is underscored by the fact
that with 20 per cent of the world's population, it has just 3.7 per cent of
world capacity for crude oil processing. It last year became a net importer
of crude oil, and demand for refined products is continuing to grow rapidly,
in line with explosive economic growth.
In 1993, China exported 3.38m tonnes of product, but imported 12.8m tonnes.
Crude imports reached 15.65m tonnes. Total output of crude last year was
143.7m tonnes from both onshore and offshore fields, but China is struggling
to maintain these production levels.
Beijing earlier this year clamped down on crude oil imports in an effort to
bring order to a chaotic local market, but Mr Li predicted that imports
would rebound next year. Buoyant demand would last for a long time to come,
he said.
