<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 94 / Signal workers urge union to open talks: Breakthrough vote
could herald end of dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Striking signal workers voted yesterday to urge the RMT union executive to
open talks with Railtrack in a breakthrough that could herald the end of the
three-month dispute.
The vote came at the annual conference of about 100 RMT signal workers'
delegates in Great Yarmouth, which resisted calls to step up the action.
A union official denied that the move was a climbdown, but until now the RMT
leadership has insisted on an interim pay rise for the signal workers as a
reward for past productivity gains before talks on restructuring could
begin.
The conference, which does not set policy, said it wanted parallel
negotiations on both past productivity and future restructuring. It also
recommended that any negotiated package be put to all signal workers in a
secret ballot.
The call for fresh talks will be discussed by the union's executive
committee today and could lead to a meeting with the employers before the
next one-day strike, due on Friday.
Railtrack, the state-owned company that runs the track network, said it
hoped the RMT executive would respond positively. 'We are prepared to talk
about anything on the table if this signals a change in attitude.'
Last night Mr Jimmy Knapp, the RMT's general secretary, said the conference
decision was 'a serious and positive move to bring Railtrack back to real
negotiations'. The union's chief negotiator, Mr Vernon Hince, added: 'This
is a genuine attempt to get talks off the ground.'
Pressure has been mounting on the union's 21-strong executive committee to
reopen talks with Railtrack.
Yesterday's unanimous vote on a resolution was drawn up at the weekend after
the signal workers' leaders had tested the mood of the delegates.
It rapidly became apparent that there was widespread desire among union
branches for a quick return to talks and a settlement of the dispute that
has already cost each signal worker more than Pounds 700 in lost pay.
The RMT stressed last night that the signal workers' move was only 'a first
step' on the road to a settlement of Britain's longest industrial conflict
since the miners' strike 10 years ago.
When the talks resume they are likely to be protracted. Initially Railtrack
had hoped to spend about three months negotiating the restructuring package
designed to transform working practices among the signalling grades.
It is now hoped a deal can be reached by September 30 - the deadline for
agreement if the signal workers are not to lose substantial benefits when
the industry's pension fund is redistributed as part of the privatisation
process.
The signal workers' conference did not call for an end to the industrial
conflict, warning that further stoppages might be necessary if negotiations
failed. The delegates rejected arbitration as a way out of the dispute.
They also stuck to their original 11 per cent pay claim for past
productivity - the demand that led to the outbreak of the dispute.
More than half the rail network is now open for services on strike days
because of the use of managers and supervisors in signal boxes.
</TEXT>
