FT  17 SEP 94 / US blocks extradition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US federal judge blocked the extradition of an escaped Irish Nationalist
and ordered his immediate release. James Joseph Smyth escaped from Northern
Ireland's Maze prison in 1983, during the biggest jailbreak in British
history. US District Judge Barbara Caulfield rejected the extradition
request after finding that Smyth would be punished on the basis of his
political opinions if returned to Northern Ireland. Smyth, 40, was released
without bail. Federal prosecutors representing the British government are
expected to appeal against the decision.
