<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / FT Guide for the Serious Investor (18): Bargain hunters back
on the road - Investing in classic cars / Prices have stalled, but the
cheaper end of the market is revving up again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The pain of burned fingers is still being endured by many who invested in
the classic and exotic car boom of the late 1980s.
Throughout this year some dispiriting dramas have been played out in the
salerooms of Brooks, Coys, Christies and other of the principal auction
houses through which a large percentage of the world's more valuable and
interesting cars changes hands.
Owners of many cars bought near the peak of the boom in 1989 have seen
values plummet to levels they would not have thought possible.
In 1989, the 'middle market' of collectibles, embracing a multitude of
Ferraris, Aston Martins, gull-wing Mercedes, SS Jaguars and other minor
exotica, spanned a price range of Pounds 200,000 to Pounds 700,000. Today,
those same cars will fetch between Pounds 25,000 and Pounds 125,000.
The top end of the market has frequently fared little better. In 1989, Aston
Martin DBR2/2, one of the illustrious Le Mans 24-Hours racing cars of the
1950s, went under the hammer at Brooks for Pounds 2.1m. In June of this
year, at the Brooks sale during the Earl of March's festival of speed at
Goodwood, bidding on its DBR2/1 sister car - in better condition and with an
even greater racing pedigree - sputtered to a halt at Pounds 840,000. The
car remained unsold.
But it's not all bad. The cheaper end of the market - that is, up to Pounds
20,000 - has become quite active again. And, in the middle market,
bargain-hunters have already reappeared in some numbers to mop up cars
reluctantly being sold by owners no longer able to withstand pressure from
their bankers - or by the banks themselves liquidating debtors' assets.
Auction house principal Robert Brooks and his colleagues acknowledge readily
that those who came to the classic-car market in the late 1980s strictly as
speculators will never be back. Nor do they expect to experience within the
forseeable future a repetition of the late 1980s bubble - 'prices were
crazy,' acknowledges Brooks.
But what the current situation does mean is that there is now plenty of
scope for wealthy individuals to indulge an enthusiasm for classic and
exotic cars, without necessarily having to pay a financial penalty for such
enthusiasm - and with at least some prospect of long-term gain.
A well-chosen chosen 'stable' of cars, bought now, as most sectors of the
classic market continue slowly to lift off the market bottom, is certain to
sustain modest value gains over the coming years.
As an example, such a stable is quite likely to include the Jaguar E-Type,
one of the most popular classics and a public sensation when it was launched
in the early 1960s as the first fairly affordable 150mph sports car.
While the prices bubble was still growing, many E-Types had Pounds
50,000-Pounds 60,000 spent on them, to bring them up to concours condition,
in the expectation by their owners that they would achieve Pounds
100,000-plus in the auction rooms.
Such cars are typically being sold for around Pounds 30,000, and by almost
any measure must be accounted a bargain if the restoration work has been
done well.
At more exalted levels, Brooks insists there is even the prospect of
substantial gains for those prepared and financially able to invest
strategically at the very top end of the market - a commitment admittedly
requiring the expenditure of several millions at least.
'If someone is prepared to make a collection of 30-40 cars, buy only the
very, very best and take an eight-to-10 year view, then I cannot think that
an investor would lose,' he maintains.
This, however, is to view the investor once again as dispassionate
speculator. Those professionally involved with the classic and historic cars
would maintain that, for such investments to make full sense, the cars
themselves must be used and enjoyed, not stashed away in a heated
motor-house.
The auction houses that dominate this esoteric trade - only around a quarter
of sales are believed to be accounted for by private treaty - are well to
the fore in promoting their use.
Coys, the Kensington-based auction house, backs the annual International
Historic Festival of Speed at Silverstone in July, where hundreds of such
cars are raced and otherwise put through their paces.
Brooks is a backer of the Earl of March at the Goodwood festival.
Neither puts up the funding out of unalloyed enthusiam - both events provide
a showcase for simultaneous auctions, and a reason for potential buyers to
converge from all around the globe in what is now unquestionably an
international market.
But the occasions do provide the proof that many owners are indeed getting
much more out of their investment than a financial return.
The sector could have provided a more appropriate alternative for a wealthy
group of individuals who asked a US investment banker, in the late 1970s,
whether they should invest in the ill-fated DeLorean sports-car project.
Back came the reply that they should put the money into wine and women
instead - 'You'll get the same return and have a lot more fun.'
Over a decade, even the few DeLoreans made have been appreciating slowly.
</TEXT>
