<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / FT Guide for the Serious Investor (17): The sport of
commoners - Investing in a racehorse / Michael Thompson-Noel bought two
shares in a racing syndicate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At York racecourse on August 17, the pulsating finish to the Gimcrack Stakes
provided a textbook study of the dramas and uncertainties on which the sport
 -and business - of horse racing are based.
The Gimcrack is a race for two-year-old colts and geldings. It is a
prestigious affair: the winning owner is invited to make a speech at the
famous Gimcrack dinner later in the year. And it is well worthwhile
financially: Pounds 61,537.80 to the winner this year, Pounds 22,690.20 to
the second, Pounds 10,820.10 to the third, down to Pounds 568.65 to the
sixth.
As this year's Gimcrack boiled to a climax, the race seemed at the mercy of
the well-fancied Fallow, which cost 26,000 guineas when bought as a yearling
in Ireland last year. (At British and Irish racehorse auctions, prices are
expressed, archaically, in guineas. A guinea used to be a pound and a
shilling - Pounds 1.05 - so Fallow cost its owner IPounds 27,300 in the
auction ring).
Before the Gimcrack, Fallow had had six races, winning three of them and
amassing prizemoney earnings of Pounds 36,885. In the Gimcrack, Fallow
breezed into the lead authoritatively and appeared to have the race at his
mercy.
But then, with a burst of acceleration that the pundits found astonishing,
another runner swooped and snatched first prize. This was Chilly Billy,
which had cost 20,000 (English) guineas as a two-year-old at auction but
lined-up for the Gimcrack with an inferior record to Fallow's. Before the
Gimcrack, Chilly Billy had raced three times without winning. It had
finished third once (admittedly at Royal Ascot). Its prizemoney prior to
York: Pounds 3,245.
Not surprisingly, Fallow started as a 5-1 co-favourite while Chilly Billy
was out with the washing at 12-1. Not that Chilly Billy was totally
unfancied. In the hours before the race he had been backed to win some large
sums. Close to home, though, Chilly Billy looked squeezed for room on the
rail and incapable of storming through.
At that moment - say 150 yards from the finishing post - you might have
concluded that Fallow was a star of the future, and might have been happy to
buy him, in that split second, for Pounds 500,000 (let us say) or even more.
Chilly Billy, on the other hand, might have struck you as an unlucky sort of
horse worth (for the sake of argument) not much more than his purchase price
last year.
How wrong you would have been. A narrow gap suddenly opened for him and
Chilly Billy flew towards the finishing line with such naked speed that it
is Chilly Billy, not Fallow, that is now worth many times his purchase
price.
This often happens in racing, though it would be an unwise man who slapped
down Pounds 20,000 or more at the yearling sales in the belief that
racehorses are an everyday investment. They are a gamble. They are not an
extremely long-odds gamble, like a lottery ticket, but they cost so much to
buy, train and race that very few show a profit or come close to covering
their costs.
In Britain, annual training and racing costs vary from about Pounds 12,000
to perhaps Pounds 20,000 a year if your horse is stabled with a star
trainer, while prizemoney is low (27 per cent of prizemoney is contributed
by owners themselves, via race entry fees).
But things are improving - a little. Prizemoney in Britain has perked up a
bit recently. And - importantly for owners - VAT arrangements have been
reformed, so that owners can claim back the 17.5 per cent VAT on horse
purchases and other racing costs.
To spread their risks, more and more owners are joining partnerships or
syndicates. This lowers costs greatly, but it does not reduce the gamble.
For instance, I could never afford to buy a Fallow or a Chilly Billy. But in
the spring of 1987 I bought two shares in a syndicate called Newmarket
Thoroughbred Racing and Chasing (NTRC), at Pounds 395 each. All told, NTRC
raised Pounds 309,285 from the public. Of that, only Pounds 147,149 was
spent on buying racehorses.
From 80 races, our prizemoney was a mere Pounds 17,198. Training fees
swallowed Pounds 69,017. Other biggish sums went on management fees, horse
transport, entry fees, VAT, secretarial and office expenses, start-up and
marketing costs, legal and professional charges - what have you.
By the time NTRC was wound-up, there was very little money left. There had
been a whirlwind of activity - horses coming and going, hopes rising and
falling. Our horses had run 80 times, but none had been remotely in the
class of Fallow or Chilly Billy. At the end, I received a tiny pay-off
cheque from the syndicate's Newmarket organisers: so far as I recall, less
than Pounds 40.
Did I enjoy myself? The answer, quite inevitably, would have to be yes and
no. Perhaps more no than yes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
