<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / FT Guide for the Serious Investor (16): Be sure it's the
best then wait 10 years - Investing in wine / If you know what you're doing,
it can still make sense to buy a good vintage early, pause until it's ready,
then sell half and drink the rest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you are very rich you must, on occasions, have something to celebrate,
and then your thoughts will descend to your cellar. A decent bottle of wine
is a natural accompaniment to a privileged life.
There was a period in the 1980s when wine got caught up in an investment
frenzy. Everyone was hooked on the idea that, by judicious buying, you could
drink for nothing. Just acquire the best vintages early and, by the time
they were ready for consumption, sell half the stock at a profit and drink
the rest for free.
This wonderful idea holds true - just. But you must be knowledgeable, and be
prepared to wait 10 years at least. And you must buy the best. If you bought
Mouton-Rothschild, a first growth claret and one of the most desirable of
wines, in 1982 you might have paid Pounds 500 for a case. You can sell this
wine at auction now for around Pounds 1,500 a case - if you can bear to let
it go.
Many investors paid over the odds for indifferent vintages and were caught
by the recession, which hit the wine market hard in 1991. This year, prices
have increased slowly but steadily at auction - where many serious buyers
acquire their supplies - and prospects look good for the autumn season. With
surplus cash earning little interest stuck in a bank, investing in blue-chip
wines is becoming attractive again.
Some wines have already shot ahead, especially the touted claret, Cheval
Blanc. A case of 1982 was Pounds 800 a year ago and now sells for nearer
Pounds 1,500. Christie's, which sold wine to the value of almost Pounds 9m
last season, recently offered five cases of 1947 Cheval Blanc, placing an
estimate of Pounds 10,000-Pounds 15,000 on the lot. It sold for Pounds
18,000.
This is exceptional, although demand for the best wines, which basically
means top growth clarets and a few select burgundies, has certainly
strengthened in the past year. In the same auction, Christie's designed a
ready-made cellar of 195 cases of the finest wines. It carried an estimate
of Pounds 200,000-Pounds 300,000 and sold for Pounds 340,000.
The wine experts are free with their advice. Serena Sutcliff, of Sotheby's,
recommends the great vintages of the 1980s, in particular 1986, 1988 and
1990. A case of Mouton Rothschild 1990 might cost up to Pounds 600 (Latour
and Margaux slightly less), but when it is ready for drinking in the early
years of the Third Millennium it should be superb, and much more costly. She
also recommends the top Sauternes of 1986, 1988, 1989, 1990, which can be
acquired for around Pounds 200 a case. The finest white wine of al,l Chateau
D'Yquem, is in a different price class: Pounds 900 for a case of 1986.
Serena Sutcliff also recommends vintage ports, especially the 1977, the best
vintage since 1963. A case of Taylor only costs Pounds 150.
If you want to celebrate now, you will have to pay much more for your wine.
The market should receive a tremendous lift in October when changes in the
local laws allows, for the first time, wine auctions to be held in New York.
At its first sale, on October 8, Sotheby's is offering a bottle of 1945
Latour, a truely great wine, for around Dollars 900 (Pounds 580). If this
seems a modest outlay, try bidding for a wine produced before the Phylloxera
disease ravaged Bordeaux, a magnum of 1870 Lafite which had once been in the
cellar of Glamis Castle. It carries an estimate of up to Dollars 20,000.
A decade ago, there was great interest in exotic old wines, especially from
the Americans. But doubts about authenticity, to say nothing of the dubious
drinking qualities of most 19th century wines, hit this market hard. Few
serious drinkers will buy wines produced earlier than 1945, and for a decade
or so after then only the top clarets stay in their prime.
Along with the first and second growth clarets, Paul Bowker of Christie's
sees potential in the best burgundies. In the past Romanee-Conte dominated
the burgundies. Now a run of good vintages in the 1980s, in particular 1983,
1985, 1986, 1989, and 1990, has increased interest in, and the value, of
these wines, raising first growths to Pounds 500 a case. The fact that the
vintages of recent years have been indifferent makes the burgundy of the
1980s a good wine for trading as well as drinking.
Of course, many people think that champagne is the wine for celebrations. It
has a much shorter life span than claret, and the French reckon that after
20 years even good champagnes are past their prime. Krug, Bollinger and Dom
Perignon are the most sought-after brands, with a mature champagne of the
late 1970s costing around Pounds 600 a case. But, as in all things, buy what
you enjoy, not what you think may appreciate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2084 Wines, Brandy and Brandy Spirits.
    P672  Investment Offices.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
