<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / FT Guide for the Serious Investor (10): Has money, lives
humbly - What makes a serious investor / For them, making money is a way of
keeping score, says Gillian O'Connor, as she looks into serious investment
mythology, and asks whether mere mortals can learn from the gods
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Serious Investor is the antithesis of the Punter. Not for him a quick
flutter on the back of a golf club tip. He regards investment as a vocation,
and all his risks are calculated.
Making money is his way of keeping score, so he probably makes a lot; but he
often lives comparatively humbly.
He spent several years working in investment management before branching out
on his own, and now usually has a rather scathing view of most professional
investment managers. He is probably American.
The father of investment analysis was Benjamin Graham, born in London 100
years ago this year, but a Wall Streeter all his life. Co-author of the
influential Security Analysis, a book more cited than read, he later wrote a
popular and comprehensible manual, The Intelligent Investor. This is still
in print today and well worth reading.
Best known as the proponent of Value Investing, Graham actually outlined two
distinct approaches to investment management: one for the defensive
investor, the man who was not very interested and not prepared to take much
risk; another for the enterprising investor.
Defensive investment
His portfolio for defensive investors was based on a bond/equity split with
the equities spread among 10-30 sound blue chips. Update his thinking to
take in the worldwide switch into equities, because of their greater
resistance to inflation, and you have the kind of portfolio most
professional investment managers recommend today. The basic concept is of a
team whose members' qualities are complementary.
Modern portfolio managers will, for instance, look for investments which
normally move in opposite directions, in order to reduce the overall risk of
the portfolio. The defensive investor's heirs are mainly found among 'top
down' managers - ones who create an identikit portfolio and then go out to
look for stocks to put in it.
Aggressive investment
The enterprising investor is a dedicated stockpicker, who pays scant
attention to portfolio theory. What he is looking for is shares which will
do significantly better than the overall market. He is quite prepared to run
a lumpy portfolio as long as all the lumps are of good quality.
Graham identified two types of share which fit the enterprising investors
needs:
Growth shares - companies whose businesses and profits were expanding both
rapidly and reliably, and whose shares were cheap in view of their
potential; and
'Bargain issues' - companies whose current worth made their shares cheap on
strictly mathematical criteria.
Being a cautious man, Graham chose to concentrate exclusively on the latter.
His criterion was that the share should be selling at not more than two
thirds of net current assets per share, ie, assets excluding all fixed
assets such as factories. Thus you count stock any cash or liquid
investments, but knock off debts to suppliers, customers and any other
creditors. You buy all shares selling at or below two thirds of net current
assets per share, and sell once the share price reaches net current asset
value. It is a purely objective mathematical system.
Graham's most famous disciple is now the world's best known investor, Warren
Buffett, the sage of Omaha and America's second richest man. All his wealth
 -Pounds 5.5bn at the last count - comes from his own investments. He began
by running an investment partnership, and now runs a public company called
Berkshire Hathaway. Berkshire Hathaway's annual reports have long been
collector's items, and the company has recently taken to charging for them.
The Buffett way
Buffett has adopted but modified Graham's belief in bargain issues. Like
Graham, he will only buy companies whose shares offer fundamental value.
But, unlike Graham, he also has subjective criteria: he will only buy good
businesses with good management and good long-term prospects. And once he
has found such a company he will continue to hold its shares until it loses
the characteristics which first attracted him. Such businesses are too rare
to be discarded lightly.
He says he buys shares as if he were buying the whole business, his criteria
being:
A business he can understand;
with favourable long-term prospects;
operated by honest and competent people;
available at a very attractive price.
The basis of this investment cocktail remains value, but there is more than
a hint of growth there as well. Other successful stockpickers blend the
ingredients in other ways. But their recipes have common elements.
Most serious investors find a method that suits them and stick to it; most
do not attempt to predict short-term stock market movements; most do much of
their own research and like finding shares that no one else thinks worth
buying; all of them are fascinated by the business of investment.
Copying the masters
Is there any way that the personal investor can emulate men such as Graham
and Buffett? The biggest obstacle is getting first-hand experience of the
markets. Many of the masters operate far away from financial centres, but
all had extensive practical experience first.
But the personal investor has the enormous advantage that he is answerable
only to himself, and so can take a longer-term view. He can retreat into
cash if he wants to, he can stick with a company going through a difficult
patch, and he need never buy unless he is really convinced that he has found
a winner.
</TEXT>
