<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / FT Guide for the Serious Investor (6): Get started with a
Pep - Tax planning / The annual maximum may not seem much, but a married
couple could have sheltered Pounds 110,400 by now
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tax planning for the very wealthy is far broader in scope than for those
with more modest means.
Although all the basic tax-planning steps of maximising personal allowances
and using tax-efficient investments still apply, wealthier investors will
find it worthwhile to engage in other tax-efficient devices, such as setting
up a trust or taking advice about offshore investments.
Tax-efficient investments
If you already have a stockbroker managing a discretionary portfolio, he is
likely, as a matter of course, to protect the portfolio against capital
gains and income tax through the use of a personal equity plan (Pep), into
which an annual maximum of Pounds 9,000 (Pounds 6,000 into a general plan
and Pounds 3,000 into a single company Pep) can be invested annually.
This may not seem a large amount, but a married couple who have made use of
Peps since they first came into existence in 1987 (and who had already used
up their 1994-95 tax-year allowance), would have sheltered Pounds 110,400 by
now.
More exotic and riskier tax-efficient investments include the new Enterprise
Investment Scheme (see page 16 of this survey) and enterprise zones. The
latter give tax relief on most of the cost of an investment in designated
commercial property, and on the interest on borrowings to fund the
investment. It is, in principle, a 10-year investment; and, since it is
potentially risky, anyone considering the investment should take
professional advice.
CGT and IHT planning
Everyone has an annual capital gains tax exemption of Pounds 5,800, which
can be used up by 'bed-and-breakfasting' shares - by selling them one day
and buying them back the next - or by realising gains in the same year as
losses.
It is also possible to delay paying CGT by reinvesting the gain in shares in
an unquoted trading company. There are other CGT mitigation measures
available to those who own their own business but, since this is a
complicated area, it is best to consult your tax adviser.
For many people wanting to protect their wealth from inheritance tax, the
use of a trust will be essential. A trust is a legal arrangement between the
person providing the funds (the settlor) and the person holding them (the
trustee) for a beneficiary.
If you want to pass money on to your adult children, an
interest-in-possession trust, confines tax made on capital gains in the
trust to be taxed at 25 per cent, rather than 40 per cent. The tax on income
will be at your children's rate of tax, rather than your own; and, provided
you survive 7 years after drafting making the trust, it can reduce an
inheritance tax bill from 40 per cent to nothing.
Trusts can also be used to protect money against the unexpected. If the
trust has been drawn up correctly and the trustees chosen wisely, your money
will be managed in accordance with your wishes, even if you fall prey to
mental illness, and after your death will prevent your wealth being eaten up
by avaricious relatives or future creditors.
Those worried that a future government might put up direct taxes or reduce a
rapidly-diminishing set of loopholes, can use existing legislation to set up
a trust.
Caroline Garnham, tax and trusts specialist at the City firm of Simmons &amp;
Simmons, says: 'The existing taxation of wealth is not riddled with
loopholes; it merely happens to be exceedingly generous. Under a Labour
government, this will undoubtedly stop. A trust is an extremely convenient
way of passing wealth to the next generation now, and so taking advantage of
the existing tax rules without losing control over the investment and
management decisions.'
Traditionally, any prospect of a Labour government has sent millions of
pounds offshore, to avoid the reimposition of exchange controls. This
process, even if the funds are held in trust, according to Garnham, is only
tax-efficient for those who are non-UK domiciled but UK resident. Otherwise,
the funds remain chargeable to income tax, capital gains tax and inheritance
tax if either the settlor or their family can benefit from it during the
settlor's lifetime.
However, the offshore trust can be used as a tax-efficient way of passing
money on to beneficiaries. As with an onshore trust, there is no CGT to pay
on death; but in an offshore trust, tax on subsequent capital gains will be
deferred until a capital payment is made to a beneficiary.
Does tax mitigation, using trusts, always involve benefiting others at your
expense or waiting until after your death before it becomes tax-effective?
Not necessarily, says Garnham. 'But in most cases if you want to have your
cake and eat it, the scheme will be based on flaws in the legislation, of
which there are now precious few.'
You can set up an offshore structure to defer CGT future gains during your
lifetime, but 'these schemes are highly complex. They are only really
appropriate for those prepared to fight if needs be,' warns Garnham.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
