<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / FT Guide for the Serious Investor (2): Made to measure -
Investment management / Fees are high, because Savile Row portfolio
treatment does not come at Marks &amp; Spencer's off-the-peg prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOANNA SLAUGHTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Their highly desirable City offices may suggest ivory towers, but the
blue-chip investment houses know that they can no longer rely on the cachet
of their name, or on 'old' money and personal recommendations, to attract
new private clients.
Competitive pressures mean that they regularly present their case to
prospective clients at 'beauty parades', and many have been converted to the
need for selective marketing and the raising of some hitherto discreet
profiles.
Even today, however, no leading investment management firm professes to
provide a private-client service for Everyman. Few, if any, will consider
managing a portfolio of equities for a client with less than Pounds 100,000
of free assets, and many require considerably larger sums. At Kleinwort
Benson the minimum is around Pounds 200,000, for example; at BZW, Pounds
250,000; at Mercury, Pounds 300,000; and at Schroders, a cool Pounds 2m.
Even when minima are not cast in stone, the annual management fee may
dictate the minimum acceptable sum. For instance, Barings' minimum fee is
Pounds 10,000 a year. Performance, therefore, would have to be red-hot for
the merchant bank to provide value to a client with less than Pounds 1m.
Clearly, Savile Row investment management does not come at Marks and
Spencer's off-the-peg prices. Most investment managers charge
percentage-based annual fees, and the minimum annual charge can vary from
the relatively modest to the very expensive. For example, the minimum fee at
Schroders is Pounds 20,000 a year.
Cazenove is among those that have retained a commission-charging structure
for private clients, however; and there are others who charge a combination
of commissions and management fees. Flemings allows its private clients to
choose.
Despite their size and their institutional clout, the best known investment
managers argue that they provide a highly personalised service for their
private clients. The common view is that no two clients are the same, and
that portfolios must be created to suit the individual, rather than to fit
in with a preconceived set of guidelines. Every private client has a bespoke
portfolio, reflecting their own particular circumstances.
There is frequent contact with clients, starting with an initial meeting to
establish their investment aims and their tolerance to risk; and great care
is taken when allocating clients to their named manager. Nicholas Bowater,
head of private clients at Credit Suisse Asset Management, says: 'We go
through a selection process, to ensure that the manager matches the client.'
Much stress is placed on empathy. As a senior partner at Cazenove has said:
'You should never be seduced by the amount of money on offer. It is much
more important to feel that we can get on with the client.'
It is certainly not unknown for an investment house to turn down a
prospective client. After all, there is little point in choosing a highly
disciplined and conservative house such as Rothschilds or Schroders if one
wishes to pursue a markedly adventurous investment strategy.
Michael Chamberlayne, chairman of Barings' private client division in
London, comments: 'Clients do come in with an inflated view of what is
possible, and I am never prepared to answer the question 'what return are
you going for?'. It is a complete non-starter.'
A considerable selling point for the leading investment houses is that both
their institutional and their private clients benefit from their depth of
research capability and their often vast global investment resources.
The managers argue that this global perspective enables them to deliver
services that are denied to the clients of smaller investment management
firms. For example, they can provide private clients with expertise in
overseas and emerging markets and international bond markets, and protect
their portfolios with derivatives and with hedging techniques.
The asset allocation in each private-client portfolio is likely to reflect
the current thinking of the investment house's experts, judiciously adjusted
for individual private-client circumstances; and the stocks will largely be
those that have passed the scrutiny of a team of analysts and researchers.
This should both add value and reduce risk. For example, no Mercury private
clients held a Polly Peck or British and Commonwealth share when these
companies ran into difficulties.
Collective investment vehicles are widely used to provide clients with
exposure in specialist and overseas markets, however. Most managers argue
that a portfolio needs to be very substantial indeed before a manager can
introduce individual overseas stocks. Cazenove puts the figure at Pounds 1m.
There is no consensus on the use, or avoidance, of in-house unit trusts,
however. Some managers stick to the firm's funds; others, such as James
Capel and Rothschilds, devote considerable research resources to analysing
all the available collective funds.
Similarly, there is no unanimity about the type of investment anagement
offered. Some firms will accept new private clients only on a discretionary
basis - Schroders, Mercury, Cazenove, Barings and Rothschild fall into this
category - while others, including Flemings, Credit Suisse, Kleinwort
Benson, James Capel and BZW, welcome both discretionary and advisory
clients.
Clearly, the bottom line for private clients is the performance the top
investment managers achieve on their behalf, and it is not easy for a
prospective client to assess this. However, a number of the biggest
investment management firms now run unit trusts that replicate the portfolio
of a wealthy private client, and these are useful shop windows on their
overall performance. Managers running these funds include Mercury,
Schroders, Cazenove, Barings and Credit Suisse.
The one thing none of the leading investment managers professes to provide
is an all-singing, all-dancing financial supermarket. They will work with a
private client's accountant and solicitor; and they may act as honest broker
if a client wants to invest in something like agricultural land. But they do
not sell life assurance or indeed general financial planning services.
The fundamental brief of virtually every private client division of a top
investment management firm is, in fact, unambiguous. It is to preserve the
real value of a private client's wealth through the management of a
carefully weighted portfolio of UK and overseas equities, domestic and
international bonds, and cash.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
