<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / FT Guide for the Serious Investor (1): When style obscures
substance - Introduction / The seriously rich can afford to pay somebody
else to do most of their worrying for them, says Barry Riley. But do they
get good value?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The seriously wealthy are by and large a discreet bunch, preferring to keep
their money out of the jealous gaze of the public and of the tax man.
Occasionally, however, publications with a vulgar inclination insist on
publishing speculative league tables of the multi-millionaires.
Although we do not have accurate statistical information on the wealth of
the rich, it does look as though serious money has become more diversified.
Once, it was mostly confined to property and family businesses, and was
directed through channels which were largely determined by tax loopholes and
exchange controls.
The legacy of those extreme distortions can still be seen in the continuing
agonies of the Lloyd's insurance market, which expanded rapidly in the
postwar period when it could be marketed as the ideal bolthole for the
seriously rich.
In their attempt to escape from heavy taxes and exchange controls, Lloyd's
Names accepted high risks which were largely overlooked but which have now
come tragically home to roost in many cases. In fact, the wealthier you are,
the fewer the risks you need to take. Only the middling rich are seriously
concerned with growth. The really wealthy are focused upon capital
preservation.
Swiss banks have made a speciality of serving the preoccupation of the
global rich with discretion and security. In this respect, Switzerland tops
the list of private investment centres, offering a powerful combination of
confidentiality, security and top-class service. But it is expensive, and
there is a pecking order of centres beneath it.
Luxembourg, for instance, has grown rapidly as the European centre for the
middling rich, cunningly combining an 'offshore' status with its membership
of the European Union. Other centres, such as Jersey and Guernsey, have
developed their own niches, in their cases in the English-speaking market.
There is big, big money in the hands of wealthy private investors. Last
year, Chase Manhattan Private Bank estimated that the offshore market alone
was worth some Dollars 2,100bn. About half of this was sourced in Europe and
the Middle East, but the much more rapidly expanding half originated in the
Far East and in Latin America. This leaves out of account, of course, the
further vast sums held onshore, especially in the US and Japan.
Of the Dollars 2,100bn, incidentally, Chase estimated 35 per cent was
managed in Switzerland. The UK, long a haven for rich Arabs, Swedes and
others, came next with 15 per cent. Luxembourg and the Channel Islands had 6
per cent each, and the Caribbean centres, which primarily hold wealth from
the US and Latin America, had 10 per cent.
The base currency is highly influential in determining investment
strategies. UK-based investors select their strategies in the context of a
historically weak currency and a higher inflation rate than has been
experienced in most countries on the continent of Europe (and slightly
higher than in the US).
The British government and the Bank of England are, it is true, proclaiming
that they have adopted a low-inflation strategy. Indeed, for the past couple
of years inflation has been higher in Germany and the US than in the UK. But
it will take years before UK investors - who can vividly remember Black
Wednesday and the collapse in sterling only two years ago - are convinced
that anything fundamental has changed.
British investors are therefore hooked on equities rather than
fixed-interest investments. Cantrade Investment Management, a private-client
fund manager in London (which happens to be an offshoot of a Swiss bank) has
devised a benchmark which it says is typical of a sizeable private client
portfolio.
The benchmark return is based on a portfolio containing 50 per cent in UK
equities, 20 per cent in overseas equities and 30 per cent in 'defensive
assets'. The last would include index-linked gilts, overseas bonds and
liquid deposits.
Investors with portfolios constructed on these lines have had a rather dull
1994 so far, with a negative return of about 8 per cent in the first six
months. However, in 1993 the return was an impressive 26 per cent, so few
investors will have been seriously worried by the latest setback.
A penalty of being merely comfortably off is that you worry about your
money. An advantage of being seriously rich is that you can afford to pay
somebody else to do most of the worrying for you. Many advisory firms in
London and elsewhere in the UK are positioning themselves to attract the
business of the financially well-endowed.
Whare should you go? The mystique of the City of London continues to attract
many British investors. Merchant banks and stockbrokers still cluster in the
Square Mile, although as far as investment management business is concerned
the practical benefits of being there are slight.
The West End and areas like Kensington are also important for private-client
business, particularly for foreigners who are familiar with this part of
London but would probably not be able to find their way from Throgmorton
Street to Threadneedle Street.
Style rather than substance dominates the advisory business. Investment
performance is rarely a sensitive factor, because clients are so
ill-informed about the results obtained by other managers (although to some
extent Cantrade may have set the cat amongst the pigeons here).
Levels of service and marketing styles are usually more important. Clients
normally like to talk to an account director who is reasonably close to
their own age, and they value continuity of relationships. At the top end of
the market, elegant addresses and butler-with-silver-tray styles are
regarded as essential.
If you are entertained to an elegant lunch at your private bank, you can be
sure that, although you will never receive a bill, it will be costing you a
small fortune. But if you have a large fortune you will be able to regard it
all as a vital part of the service.
</TEXT>
