<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / UK Company News: US advance helps Keller to Pounds 3.01m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WOLFFE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Keller, the international ground engineering company, reported a 40 per cent
rise in pre-tax profits for the six months to June 30 after strong sales in
North America.
Profits rose from Pounds 2.15m to Pounds 3.01m in its first results since
flotation in April, when shares were priced at 130p giving a market
capitalisation of Pounds 72.8m. Yesterday the shares closed up 3p at 129p.
Turnover was Pounds 89.1m (Pounds 69.5m), including Pounds 10.5m from
acquisitions, and operating profit rose 28 per cent to Pounds 3.64m (Pounds
2.83m) after a Pounds 400,000 contribution from Case International, the
Chicago-based foundation engineer acquired in January.
Mr Michael West, chief executive, said: 'Our order books at the half-year
were well ahead of the same time last year, and that stronger order book was
still in place at the end of August.'
In North America sales increased from Pounds 13.3m to Pounds 28m, helped by
the Case purchase, for profits of Pounds 1.33m, compared with Pounds
789,000.
In Germany trading volumes remained high although the group, a former
engineering offshoot of GKN, warned of tightening margins in western Germany
where market conditions were increasingly competitive. Continental Europe
contributed profits of Pounds 1.75m (Pounds 1.79m) on turnover of Pounds
47.2m (Pounds 43.5m).
UK turnover was Pounds 13.9m (Pounds 12.7m) and profits more than trebled to
Pounds 345,000 (Pounds 101,000), reflecting improved trading conditions and
the start of infrastructure projects on the Jubilee underground line and
Heathrow Airport rail link.
Group net interest costs fell to Pounds 631,000 (Pounds 689,000). Net
borrowings at the period end were Pounds 4.4m for gearing which would
reduced to 14 per cent.
An interim foreign income dividend of 0.5p is being paid from earnings per
share up at 4.5p (2.4p).
</TEXT>
